e development of the\ncompany.s magnificent property by\nGeneral Manage* George E. Gunn,\nand a financial statement by Treas\nurer Frank W. Holmes. The latter\ncovers a period from February. 1907,\nto May 1. of this year, and reads as\nfollows:\nBalance Sheet.\nCapital stock unissued $300,000.00\nProperty 626.793.33\nMachinery and mine\nequipment 9.730.28\nI Office furniture. 513,84\nDevelopment 37.774.52\nMine Supplies 3.888.08\nCash on hand:\nNew York $14,907.03\nMine 2.320.25 17.227.28\n$1,002,250.45\nCaJital account. $1,000,000.00\nInterest 2,250.45\n$1,002.250.45\nCadi Statement.\nRECEIPTS.\nSab 100,000 shares\nstbek .$100,000.00\nInterest 2.250.45\n1 02.250.45\nDISHCRStC.M ENTS.\nI Property 29.106.39\nBuildings 0.063.12\nMachinery and mine\nequipment 8,603.02\nOffice fruniture. 4 18.84\nDevelojunent. 37,774.52\nMine supplies. 3.057.28\nCash on hand:\nN. Y $1 4,907.03\nj Mine 2.320.25 17.227.28\n$102,250.49\nManager George E. Gunn's repo ft\nis brief and covers the location, ex\ntent. e juipment and operation of the\nj mines/since the organization of the\npresent company and is evidently in\ntended to only give a correct idea of\neverything without going into great\ndetail And in passing it may be\nsaid hat the most startling and sig\nnificant disclosures in the history of\nthe* mines of the company have been\nmade since the manager's report was\nforwiarded to the New York head\nquarters. .Most of the information\ncontained in the report is familiar to\nI New?; readers on account of the\nmanagement's willingness to occa\nsionally give news out touching the\nprogress of developments. For alj\nthat, there are some things mention\ned that will sound well, coming of\nfle fatly from Manager Gunn, so. for\nI the benefit of those w ho may not\nsee he report, a few paragraphs are\ntaken from It. as follows:\n\u2018\u2018jlTp to present wrting no attempt\nhas been made to block out the ore\nbod'es, and the very nature of the de\nvelopment up to this time precludes\nthe figuring of any ore bodies as ore\nactually in sight.' There are, how\never, several thousand tons of\nstraight smelting ore, averaging w\nper cent copper, at present available\nin the workings, while tin* tonnage\nof the concentrating product will be\nfound large.\n\"On the dumps it is estimated\nthere are about 1,000 tons of smelt\nlug ores, averaging 5.50 per cent\n(copper, and 1,000 tons concentrating\nores The better product from the\nmines generally will be found to Ik*\na straight smelting ore. although a\nlarge quantity of the lower grade\nores will be subject to treatment by\nconcentration, the best method of ex\ntraction being determined up to pres\nent on account of changes in charac\nter of ores uncovered.\n\"The Mason Valiev mines were\nworked in the earlier times and the\namount of surface workings indicate\nthat large shipments were made of\nifiigh grade oxidised ores. With mod\nernized methods the properties of the\nMason Valley Mines Co. are now de.\n1 eloping into large copper ore bodies\nof a c lass carrying good values and\nsubject to treatment locally by con\ncentrating and smelting.\n\"From point of accessibility the\ni property is most favorably located,\nmain workings being reached by ex\nceptionally good wagon road, con\nstructed by the company. From Ma\nson Valley to the Walker river .he\ndistance in air line is one and one\nhalf miles, the river carrying an\nabundance of water all the year\nj round, an extremely favorable condi\ntion if it is found necessary to build\na plant for treatment of ores in c lose\nproximity to the mines.\u201d\nHEAT PROSTRATIONS.\nCHICAGO, June 23. Seven pros\nit rations had been reported in Chl\ncago up to noon today from the heat\nwhich prevailed with but slight di\ninlnutlon for the past 24 hours, and\nj which has been responsible for two\ndeaths.\n1\nTWO KILLED IN DUEL,\nALBUQUERQUE, N. M June 22.\n\u2014R *1. SnBier and Edwarif Jones,\ncattlemen, were l oth killed In a duel j\nthis evening. The fight took place\nnear St. Vraln, N. M 200 miles east 1\nof here The men were neigh hors1\nand quarreled over a cattle trade,\nflans were drawn and fifed simul\ntaneously. Both men were Instantly\nkilled. The quarrel Is said to have\nbeen the outgrowth of an old rend.\nBoth men were wealthy and highly\nrespected.\n\nHAYES GREEN PARK HOTEL\nFirst Clam Furnished Rooms\nAiwa)* Quint ami\nMISS MAYES, Proprietress.\nSMELTER LIVERY COM.\n\\Ve*t of (Nd Power Houae,\nM'taLL, NKVADA.\n(a:\\Plt \\L THANHFKIt A\\l> KKKD\nSTAIUJ:.\nKig> or saddle horw'H may In* had to j\ngo to the fishing ground*.\nI What Is the liveliest town iu I\njS the District? Pj\njl Where in tlie most building H\n\u00a7j| iM-ing done? ;m\nE| Where in the most niohV v in 'S\nm circulation? B\nft RIEPETOWN, of tours,** I\nB ,f >'ou want \u00bbny \u00abf B\nyi lot* at promoters\u2019 price*. H\n,M you will have to get busy. H\nI ELY INVESTMENT CO. I\nJ Sole Agents for Owner#. pf\n\n\u201cIf you have It from ns lt>\nright.\"\nW.H.BISHOP\nJEWELER\nWATCHES\nDIAMONDS\nJEWELRY\n*vqt if 1\nNorthern Hotel llldg.\n-*__\n-*,-a\n.ifcoalrtns i :ril. ,\u00ab.#iojfr iff W **i\nao sniff* ___ _\n^v-r *ki Get off at Ely City and Stop at\n;-i l\u00ab d S i i I _ If\nThe Steptoe Hotel\n\u2018J-Finest Hotel in Eastern Nevada. Handsomest\nand best conducted Cafe in the state. j\nFRANCIS HLKIN. Manager.\n\u2019d Fmhieriy of the Palato and St. Fran\nod' r tit Hotels, San Frnnrleco\niM to i'. tfi\nV v ,8101.' I I\u2019ll J JB! r I V. di.:l I. V V-'\nP MW* w. ...-r-1 1 1\ni a __- 1","height":"23496","width":"16208"}}
